    <exdesc keyword="acc_test">
      <description>
&amp;gACCEPTED OOC TEST&amp;n
.
The following are examples of the types of questions that should be 
posed to the Accepted and the sorts of things she is expected to know 
and be able to do. The person giving the test should use her own 
discretion, as well, asking any additional questions she feels are 
necessary not only to test the student's ability, but to help improve 
that ability. 
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Have the Accepted discuss the rules for Accepted and why each is 
important. 
.
Have the Accepted discuss which Ajah she wishes to join and both the 
character's IC reasons for choosing this Ajah as well as the player's 
OOC reasons. She should demonstrate a clear understanding of the Ajah's 
purpose. For example, answers that would indicate a lack of 
understanding: &quot;I want to be green because I already have two warders 
lined up to bond.&quot; &quot;I want to be yellow because I want Heal Gentling.&quot; 
Although these might be adequate OOC reasons (just barely), they are 
somewhat lacking in IC justification. 
.
Have the Accepted discuss the bond and her view on the relationship 
between warders and Sedai, bearing in mind the particular Ajah she is 
choosing. 
.
Quiz the Accepted on the stereotypical views the guild has towards 
other guilds and how these vary or coincide with her own views. 
.
Have the Accepted discuss which of the Shadowspawn she considers most 
dangerous and why. 
.
Have the Accepted demonstrate forming a ward to keep out vermin. 
.
Ask the Accepted to discuss the advantages and disadvantages of 
linking. 
.
Have the Accepted discuss the Healing weave and her ability with it. 
.
Go through two or three rounds of sparring with weaves to check the 
Accepted's facility. Be wary of closed emotes and supersedai syndrome. 
.
Have the accepted demonstrate tying weaves and destroying knots. 
.
Ask the Accepted which areas she thinks she needs most needs to 
improve. 
.
&amp;rNote:&amp;n Most of these questions do not really have a specific &quot;right&quot; 
response. They are designed to ascertain if the Accepted is ready to 
play an Aes Sedai character on her own. 
</description>
    </exdesc>
    <exdesc keyword="combat">
      <description>
&amp;gEMOTE CHANNELING IN COMBAT&amp;n
.
Demonstrate to the student how to emote combat involving channeling. 
Eventually this document may be expanded into a more comprehensive 
guide. For now, it is just a sort of checklist of things the author 
feels should be addressed. Make sure that the student keeps the 
following concepts in mind: 
.
Keep the Oaths in mind.
Do not use closed emotes.
Always respond to your opponent's emote.
Tend towards wraps and shields whenever possible.
Keep in mind that combat weaves are fatiguing. Saidar is not as well 
suited to destructive weavings.
Enter combat as a last resort.
Keep your strengths and weaknesses in mind.
Emphasize defense instead of offense.
Be aware of your surroundings. Read the room description.
Use this lesson as an opportunity to instruct sliceweave.
Coordinate with your warder(s). They don't have that pesky third oath.
</description>
    </exdesc>
    <exdesc keyword="bond">
      <description>
&amp;gNATURE OF THE BOND&amp;n
.
Bonding is a fairly new thing, introduced around the time of the 
formation of the White Tower. The bond is formed of Spirit. Once bonded 
an Aes Sedai and her Gaidin are constantly aware each of the other's 
physical and emotional status. This doesn't mean that an Aes Sedai can 
read her gaidin's mind, or vice versa, simply that they can sense 
feelings such as worry, fear, pleasure, pain and even jealousy. This 
connection exists regardless of distance and is like a small, separate 
part within a person's mind that represents his or her bondmate. 
.
There are several advantages that warders gain through the bond. They 
heal faster than other people and can last longer without food, water 
or sleep. They share with their Aes Sedai the ability to sense the 
close presence of shadowspawn (not darkfriends, shadowspawn) and their 
dreams are shielded against those who can manipulate Tel'aran'rhiod. 
.
The advantages to an Aes Sedai are obvious in that she has somebody to 
protect her when she is unable to channel, channelling would be unsafe, 
or she is too weak or hurt. She is also able to draw strength from her 
Warder. 
.
Unfortunately, this bond means that when one bondmate dies the other 
feels a tremendous loss, also known as bondloss. Many Gaidin have been 
known to go insane or seek their own deaths after the loss of their Aes 
Sedai. Aes Sedai feel incredible loss, grief, and loneliness for a long 
period of time after the death of a Gaidin. 
.
Many Aes Sedai believe that distraction is the best way to get over 
bondloss, and will rebond a gaidin who has lost his Aes Sedai in an 
attempt to stop him from suicide. 
.
Jane spins out threads of Spirit woven into a complex web. As she 
reaches down and places her fingertips on the kneeling man's forehead, 
she sinks the weave into his skull, forming a permanent link between 
him and herself. 
.
There are OOC obligations that go along with the bond. A warder is a 
companion, a guard and a servant. They are not typically lovers. There 
is, of course, no hard and fast rule that works for all players. In 
general, however, it is a very good idea to have a long OOC discussion 
with a potential bondmate beforhand. Make certain that both parties are 
on the same page in their view of the bond and the relationship. Long 
observation has taught this author that bonds based on &quot;romantic&quot; 
relationships rarely last. Before bonding someone, make absolutely 
certain that he understands what you expect from a warder. It will save 
a lot of trouble and bond-passing in the long run. That is the reason 
for this being an actual taught lesson instead of just a reading. This 
way if someone has a series of bad bonds after completely ignoring this 
advice, we will know that we have at least tried. 
.
NOTE: The weave is not actually taught until very late in the student's 
education. Typically, it is saved until right before she is raised to 
the shawl. However, there have been several incidents of Accepted 
learning the weave by seeing it used. Therefore, it is included in the 
Accepted Syllabus. The IC repercussions of bonding while still Accepted 
are severe. Typically, punishment includes delaying the Accepted's 
promotion to the shawl for a lengthy period of time and forcefully 
transferring the bond to someone else. 
</description>
    </exdesc>
    <exdesc keyword="nov_test">
      <description>
&amp;gNOVICE TEST&amp;n
.
The following are examples of the types of questions that should be 
posed to the Novice and the sorts of things she is expected to know and 
be able to do. The person giving the test should use her own 
discretion, as well, asking any additional questions she feels are 
necessary not only to test the student's ability, but to help improve 
that ability. 
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
Have the Novice tell what the rules are for novices and the reasoning 
behind each of the rules. 
.
Have the novice demonstrate her ability to emote grasping the One 
Power, varying the amount she holds, and releasing. 
.
Quiz the Novice on her abilities in each of the five powers. Make 
certain that she has a firm understanding of her own IC strengths and 
weaknesses and that these things are plausible. 
.
Have the Novice perform some hypothetical task that can be done in more 
than one way to test her tendencies. For example, have her bend a thin 
piece of metal with the One Power. This could be done with Earth, or 
Air, or even Fire. There is no single answer that is always correct, as 
such. The importance of the question is to see if the student has a 
grasp not just of how the One Power works, but of her own limitations 
and strengths with it. 
.
Have the novice explain the pecking order among the Aes Sedai. Likely, 
this will just be a matter of her regurgitating the information in the 
hierarchy lecture, but serves the purpose of making sure that she does 
at least look at it. 
.
Ask a random question about the history of the White Tower, just to 
affirm that the Novice has read it. 
.
Explain why each of the three oaths is important and why they should be 
followed at all times. 
.
Have the Novice list some examples of when the hierarchy is not to be 
followed. (i.e. an Accepted given privileges sometimes held only by aes 
sedai, etc...who is able to give them the authority) 
.
Trick question: Ask the student to demonstrate her emote channeling 
ability by performing some impossible task. For example, ask her to 
demonstrate autolevitation (lifting herself into the air) or 
shapeshifting or some such. It does not matter what the task is, as 
long as it is something that would not be possible in the theme of the 
Wheel of Time world. One of the philosophies behind this syllabus is 
that good instruction is a better method of deterring &quot;unrealistic&quot; RP 
than some complex Talent Policy. Therefore, it is important that we 
never promote someone who believes that she can polevault herself 
through the air and land safely using the one power or other such 
unlikely things. 
.
Ask why the Novice wishes to be an Aes Sedai, both IC reasons for the 
character and OOC reasons for the player. 
.
&amp;RNOTE:&amp;n This should not be viewed simply as a test. It is also somewhat 
instructional. It should not be terribly unusual for someone to fail 
the first time, but they should walk away from the test knowing why 
they failed and what they should work on. It cannot be stressed enough 
that passing someone who does not really grasp the concepts is not 
&quot;being nice&quot; to them. If someone cannot adequately emote channel or 
play the role of an Accepted, she should not be raised. If she is 
passed without meeting the accepted standards and then demonstrates 
that lack in public it will not only make the guild as a whole look 
bad, but result in possible embarrassment and/or ridicule for the 
student. Aes Sedai should be respected (or feared), not laughed at 
behind their backs. 
</description>
    </exdesc>
    <exdesc keyword="adv2">
      <description>
&amp;W(continued from adv_emote)&amp;n

&amp;WPose:&amp;n
Pose is like an emote, except that it does not start with the 
character's name. It is useful for variety. It is important, however, 
that one always identify herself in the pose. Avoid things like: 
.
&amp;Cpose Nodding slowly, she smiles at the man.&amp;n 
.
Make it clear who is doing the pose, such as: 
.
&amp;Cpose Nodding slowly, Jane smiles at the man.&amp;n 
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
&amp;WCemote:&amp;n
Cemote is a command for channeling emotes. Where pemote has two parts, 
cemote has three. The first part is an emote seen by other female 
channelers. The second is a pose seen by male channelers. The third is 
a pose seen by non-chans. In most situations this is way too slow and 
cumbersome to use in RP. Much like pemote, it is useful for dealing 
with people who have trouble keeping their IC and their OOC separated. 
An example would be a room with several women in it and one or more 
Asha'man. One one embraces the one power. If the Asha'man is played by 
a poor RPer, he will likely zero in on exactly the woman who embraced, 
even though all he could really tell would be that someone had 
embraced, not who. Cemote is ideal for these situations. Example: 
.
Jane's player types: 
.
&amp;Ccemote embraces Saidar, slowly being enveloped by the golden glow.|Your 
skin tingles slightly in that tell-tale indication that a woman is 
channeling nearby.&amp;n 

.
Other female chans in the room would see: 
.
&amp;cJane embraces Saidar, slowly being enveloped by the golden glow.&amp;n 
.
Male chans would see: 
.
&amp;cYour skin tingles slightly in that tell-tale indication that a woman is 
channeling nearby.&amp;n 
.
Non-chans would see nothing, as the third part of the cemote was not 
added. ICly, they would notice nothing anyway. An example of a cemote 
that includes all three parts: 
.
&amp;Ccemote weaves flows of Air to stir up a light breeze in the plaza, 
blowing from east to west.|Your skin tingles to indicate a woman is 
channeling nearby as a light breeze springs up in the plaza, blowing 
from east to west.|A light breeze springs up in the plaza, blowing from 
east to west.&amp;n 
.
Other female chans in the room would see: 
.
&amp;cJane weaves flows of Air to stir up a light breeze in the plaza, 
blowing from east to west.&amp;n 
.
Male chans would see: 
.
&amp;cYour skin tingles to indicate a woman is channeling nearby as a light 
breeze springs up in the plaza, blowing from east to west.&amp;n 
.
Non-chans would see: 
.
&amp;cA light breeze springs up in the plaza, blowing from east to west.&amp;n 
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
&amp;WChanneling for Non-Chans:&amp;n
If no other chans are in the RP, there is little need for always 
describing the flows or the glow of Saidar. They can't see them anyway. 
It is important, however, to still avoid using closed emotes. An 
example: 
.
&amp;cJane frowns at Joe, her hands on her hips and her foot tapping 
impatiently. Suddenly the air shimmers around him as she attempts to 
wrap him with the One Power.&amp;n 
</description>
    </exdesc>
    <exdesc keyword="adv_emote">
      <description>
&amp;gADVANCED EMOTE CHANNELING&amp;n
.
The purpose of this OOC lesson is to improve the quality and 
entertainment value of the student's channeling emotes. Some of these 
principles apply to all types of RP, but some are specific to 
channeling. The lesson should expose the student to the following 
concepts: 
.
&amp;WDetail:&amp;n
One simple method for improving emotes is to add minor details. This 
helps the audience visualize the scene better and also helps avoid 
ambiguity. Adding hand gestures or facial expressions to an emote is 
simple, but it adds greatly to the scene. An extra quality that can be 
noted in channeling emotes is the glow of Saidar. It brightens as one 
draws more of the Power and dims as she draws less. Do not confuse 
detail with verbosity. Some people feel that a long emote equals a good 
emote. This is not entirely accurate. More detail in an emote is good. 
Just adding garbage to pad the length of an emote is not good. Avoid 
putting a dozen actions into one emote simply to increase the length. 
Example of a long, bad emote: 
.
&amp;cJane weaves a fireball at Joe. Jane weaves a lightning bolt at Joe. 
Jane tosses another fireball from each hand at Joe. Jane tries to 
gentle Joe.&amp;n 
.
There is no detail in that emote, just several actions. An example of a 
detailed emote without too much action: 
.
&amp;cJane embraces Saidar and spins out a thick thread of Air to loop around 

the handle of the kettle. The golden glow around her brightens, her 
brow furrowing in concentration, as she draws in more of the One Power 
to lift the kettle off the stove. She gestures casually towards the 
table as the kettle begins to float towards it.&amp;n 
.
This is much preferable to something like: 
.
&amp;cJane channels air to lift the kettle.&amp;n 
-----------------------------------------------------------------------
&amp;WPemote:&amp;n
Pemote is one of our emote-like commands that can be used to spruce up 
our RP. It is a personal emote or targetted emote. It is used to send 
one emote to the target and a separate emote to the rest of the room. 
It is useful for channeling emotes, such as Healing, where the target 
receives much more information than the rest of the observers. In 
non-channeling emotes, it is useful for such things as kicking an 
overly talkative companion in the leg beneath the table. For example, 
if one typed: 
.
&amp;Cpemote Joe weaves flows of Air, Water and Spirit together into a 
complex skein. She places her hands on your head and passes the weave 
throughout your body, causing a chill to ripple through you as the 
wounds begin to knit closed.|places her hands on Joe's head and passes 
a complex skein of Air, Water and Spirit through his body, healing his 
wounds.&amp;n 
.
Joe would see: 
.
&amp;cJane weaves flows of Air, Water and Spirit together into a complex 
skein. She places her hands on your head and passes the weave 
throughout your body, causing a chill to ripple through you as the 
wounds begin to knit closed.&amp;n 
.
The rest of the room would see: 
.
&amp;cJane places her hands on Joe's head and passes a complex skein of Air, 
Water and Spirit through his body, healing his wounds.&amp;n 
.
In most situations, pemote is not very useful. It is a lot of extra 
typing. When it is useful is when dealing with people who have trouble 
separating what they see from what their characters see. In a 
non-channeling example, Jane's player types: 
.
&amp;Cpemote joe frowns deeply, but remains silent, as she kicks you in the 
ankle beneath the table.|frowns deeply but says nothing.&amp;n 
.
Joe would see: 
.
&amp;cJane frowns deeply, but remains silent, as she kicks you in the ankle 
beneath the table.&amp;n 
.
The rest of the room sees: 
.
&amp;cJane frowns deeply but says nothing.&amp;n 
.
There are many poor RPers that if this had been done as an emote, would 
have suddenly ICly known that Jane surreptitiously kicked Joe. They can 
be gotten around with pemote. 

&amp;W(continued in adv2)&amp;n
</description>
    </exdesc>
    <exdesc keyword="improv">
      <description>
&amp;gBASIC WEAVE IMPROVISATION&amp;n
.
This OOC lesson should teach the student how to work out on her own how 
to emote weaves not specifically taught in the syllabus. Examples would 
be freezing water or putting out a fire. All the possible weaves can't 
be covered in this lesson. That -is- sort of the point of the lesson. 
.
The simplest solution that still satisfies the conditions of the 
problem is usually the best solution. Molding clay is a good example. 
One could channel water to moisten the clay and make it easier to work. 
Then one could use Fire to warm it and make it more malleable. Then 
once it is moist and warm enough, one could use flows of Air to 
manipulate it. The simplest solution, however, would be just to use 
flows of Earth. 
.
Something else to consider, and even emphasize, during this lesson is 
the student's own strengths and weaknesses in the One Power. In the 
previous example of molding clay, Earth would be the ideal power to 
use. However, there are cases where the student is totally inept at 
weaving Earth, but perhaps has a strong affinity for weaving Air. 
Sometimes the simplest solution doesn't work because the student's 
strengths and weaknesses with the One Power do not allow it to. 
.
Another emphasis of the lesson should be encouraging the student to 
consider the information in the Flow Theory lesson when constructing 
multiple thread weaves. 
.
Another topic that should be covered is splitting of flows. It is made 
rather clear early on in the series that it is very difficult for most 
Aes Sedai to do multiple things at once. Since every last novice seems 
to think that she is the next Caraighan Maconar, doing two weaves at 
once should be possible, but not at first. A young novice would have 
enough trouble dealing with one weave. At any event, even a full Sedai 
who does four things at once should be made to see the error of her 
ways and encouraged never to do so again.
</description>
    </exdesc>
